ficial site]\n*[http://www.medart.pitt.edu/image/England/Bristol/StMaryRedcliffe/Bristol-StMarysRed.html St Mary's Redcliffe Parish Church&nbsp;\u2013 dimensions and plans]\n\n{{Greater Churches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Mary Redcliffe}}\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1872]]\n[[Category:12th-century churches in the United Kingdom|Redcliffe]]\n[[Category:15th-century church buildings in England|Redcliffe]]\n[[Category:Church of England church buildings in Bristol|Redcliffe]]\n[[Category:Diocese of Bristol|Redcliffe]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed churches in Bristol|Redcliffe, St Mary]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Bristol]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bristol]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name = St Mary Redcliffe\n| fullname = \n| other name = \n| image = St_Mary_Redcliffe_church.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = St Mary Redcliffe from the north\n| pushpin map = Bristol\n| pushpin label position = \n| pushpin map alt = \n| pushpin mapsize = \n| relief = \n| map caption = \n| coordinates = {{coord|51.4482|-2.5899|}}\n| osgraw = <!--  TEXT -->\n| osgridref = <!-- {{gbmappingsmall| TEXT}} -->\n| location = Redcliffe Way, [[Bristol]], BS1 6NL\n| country = England\n| denomination = [[Church of England]]\n| previous denomination = [[Catholic Church]]\n| churchmanship = [[Broad Church]]/[[Liberal Anglo-Catholicism|Liberal Catholic]]\n| membership = \n| attendance = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/|Church website}}\n| former name = \n| bull date = \n| founded date = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} - but see note below -->\n| founder = \n| dedication = \n| dedicated date = \n| consecrated date = \n| cult = \n| relics = \n| events = \n| past bishop = \n| people = \n| status = Active\n| functional status = [[Parish church]]\n| heritage designation = \n| designated date = \n| architect = \n| architectural type = \n| style = [[Perpendicular Gothic]]\n| years built = \n| groundbreaking = \n| completed date = 15th century\n| construction cost = \n| closed date = \n| demolished date = \n| capacity = \n| length = {{convert|240|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|44|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| width nave = {{convert|59|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|54|ft|9|in|m|abbr=on}}\n| diameter = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| other dimensions = \n| floor count = \n| floor area = <!-- {{convert| }} -->\n| spire quantity = \n| spire height = {{convert|292|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| materials = \n| bells = \n| bells hung = \n| bell weight = <!-- {{long ton|0| }} -->\n| parish = St. Mary Redcliffe with Temple Bristol and St. John the Baptist, Bedminster\n| deanery = Bristol South\n| archdeaconry = [[Archdeaconry of Bristol]]\n| episcopalarea = \n| diocese = [[Diocese of Bristol]]\n| province = [[Province of Canterbury]]\n| bishop = \n| rector = \n| vicar = The Revd Canon Dan Tyndall <br /> The Revd Kat Campion-Spall (Associate Vicar)\n| priestincharge = \n| priest = \n| asstpriest = The Revd Anthony Everitt\n| curate = The Revd Aggy Palairet\n| honpriest = The Revd Peter Dill\n| asstcurate = \n| nonstipendiaryminister = \n| minister = \n| assistant = \n| deacon = \n| reader = \n| student intern = \n| organistdom = Andrew Kirk\n| director = \n| organist = Claire Alsop, Graham Alsop\n| organscholar = Matthew Brown\n| chapterclerk = \n| laychapter = \n| warden = Elizabeth Shanahan, Richard Wallace\n| verger = Matthew Buckmaster (Head Verger), Judith Reading, Anthony Scott, Paul Thomas\n| businessmgr = Roseanna Wood\n| liturgycoord = \n| reledu = \n| rcia = \n| youthmin = Becky Macron\n| flowerguild = \n| musicgroup = [http://www.stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/choirs-of-st-mary-redcliffe.html The Choirs of St Mary Redcliffe]\n| parishadmin = \n| serversguild = \n| Sacristan = \n}}\n'''St Mary Redcliffe''' is an [[Anglican parish church]] located in the [[Redcliffe, Bristol|Redcliffe]] district of [[Bristol]], England. The church is a short walk from [[Bristol Temple Meads railway station|Bristol Temple Meads station]]. The church building was constructed from the 12th to the 15th centuries, and it has been a place of Christian worship for over 900 years. The church is renowned for the beauty of its [[Gothic architecture]] and is classed as a Grade I [[listed building]] by [[Historic England]].<ref name=nhle>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1218848 |desc=Church of St Mary Redcliffe |grade=I |accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref> It was famously described by [[Queen Elizabeth I]] as \"the fairest, goodliest, and most famous parish church in England.\"{{sfn|Burrough|1970|pp=13-14}}{{sfn|Little|1967}}\n\nLittle remains of the earliest churches on the site although a little of the fabric has been dated to the 12th century. Much of the current building dates from the late 13th and 14th centuries when it was built and decorated by wealthy merchants of the city whose tomb and monuments decorate the church. The spire fell after being struck by lightning in 1446 and was not rebuilt until 1872. Little of the original stained glass remains following damage in the [[English Civil War]] with extensive new glass being added during the [[Victorian era]]. The tower contains 15 bells designed for full-circle English-Style [[change ringing]]. Other music in the church is provided by several choirs and the [[Harrison & Harrison]] organ.\n\n==History==\nThe first church on this site was built in Saxon times, as the [[Port of Bristol]] first began.<ref>{{cite web|title=Your Visit&nbsp;\u2014 Heritage|url=http://stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/your-visit/heritage/|publisher=St Mary Redcliffe|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> In [[Middle Ages|medieval times]], St Mary Redcliffe, sitting on a red cliff above the [[River Avon (Bristol)|River Avon]], was a sign to seafarers, who would pray in it at their departure, and give thanks there upon their return. The church was built and beautified by Bristol's wealthy merchants, who paid to have masses sung for their souls and many of whom are commemorated there.{{sfn|Jenkins|1999}}\n\n[[File:St Mary Redcliffe Church, Bristol, BRO Picbox-7-StMR-9, 1250x1250.jpg|thumb|left|An etching of St Mary Redcliffe from the North West c. 1850.]]\nParts of the church date from the beginning of the 12th century. Although its plan dates from an earlier period, much of the church as it now stands was built between 1292 and 1370, with the south aisle and transept in the Decorated Gothic of the 13th century and the greater part of the building in the late 14th century [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular]]. The patrons included Simon de Burton, Mayor of Bristol, and William I Canynges, merchant, five times Mayor of Bristol and three times MP. In the 15th century Canynges' grandson, the great merchant [[William II Canynges]], also five times Mayor and three times MP, assumed responsibility for bringing the work of the interior to completion and filling the windows with stained glass. In 1446 much of this work was damaged when the spire was struck by lightning, and fell, causing damage to the interior; however the angle of the falling masonry and the extent of the damage is unclear.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Tower Vaulting&nbsp;\u2014 Archaeological Survey|url=http://stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/files/2014/08/St-Mary-Redcliffe-NW-tower-vaulting-report-revised-assembled-reduced.pdf|website=St Mary Redcliffe|publisher=Jerry Sampson Buildings Archaeology|accessdate=29 March 2015|year=2014}}</ref> Although the spire was to remain damaged for the next 400 years, Canynges continued in his commitment to restore and beautify the church. He took Holy Orders after the death of his wife, and is buried in the church.<ref name=About>{{cite web|url=http://www.about-bristol.co.uk/chu-12.asp|title=About Bristol&nbsp;\u2013 St. Mary Redcliffe}}</ref> Other families associated with St Mary Redcliffe include the Penns, the Cabots, the Jays, the [[Richard Amerike|Ameryk]]s and the Medes.{{sfn|Jenkins|1999}}\n[[File:Panoramic view of St Mary Redcliffe nave.jpg|thumb|The nave of St Mary Redcliffe]]\nIn 1571, the school that was to become [[St Mary Redcliffe and Temple School]] was formed in a chapel in the churchyard. The church and school have remained closely linked in many aspects of their operations.\n\nThe 17th century saw the loss of many of the church fittings and much of the [[stained glass]] during the [[English Reformation|Reformation]] and the [[English Civil War]]. During the reign of [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]], and partially funded by her, the interior of St. Mary Redcliffe was refitted in the [[Baroque]] style.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/18thCentury.htm |title=18th century |accessdate=13 May 2007 |work=St Mary Redcliffe |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070104003556/http://stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/18thCentury.htm |archivedate=4 January 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Thomas Chatterton]], whose father was [[Sexton (office)|sexton]] of St Mary Redcliffe, was born in the house next to the church in 1752. He studied the church records in a room above the south porch, and wrote several works which he attempted to pass as genuine medieval documents. He committed suicide in London at the age of seventeen.{{sfn|Burrough|1970|pp=13-14}} In 1795 the church saw the marriages of [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]] to Sara Fricker and [[Robert Southey]] to Sara's sister Elizabeth.{{sfn|Cottle|2014|p=189}}{{sfn|Traill|2011|p=20}}\n\nThe upper part of the [[spire]], missing since being struck by lightning in 1446,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.about-bristol.co.uk/chu-12.asp |title= St Mary Redcliffe |accessdate=13 May 2007 |format= |work=About Bristol}}</ref> was reconstructed in 1872 to a height of {{convert|292|ft|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Burrough|1970|pp=13-14}} Funds for the spire rebuilding had been raised by the Canynges Society, the Friends of St Mary Redcliffe, which was formed in 1843.<ref>{{cite news|title=Restoration of St. Mary, Redcliffe|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000034/18430107/030/0008|accessdate=30 March 2015|work=Bristol Mercury|date=7 January 1843|page=8| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> They raised most of the \u00a340,000 needed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Restoration of Redcliffe Church. Completion of the Spire|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000264/18720501/011/0003|accessdate=30 March 2015|work=Western Daily Press|date=1 May 1872|page=3| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The {{convert|1|t}} capstone was laid by the Mayor, Mr William Procter Baker, at the top of the scaffolding.<ref>{{cite news|title=Restoration of Redcliffe Church. Laying the Cap-stone of the Spire|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000034/18720511/016/0006|accessdate=30 March 2015|work=Bristol Mercury|date=11 May 1872|page=6| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>{{sfn|Fells|2014|pp=79-81}} Because of the effect of environmental pollution on the [[Dundry Stone]], further repairs to the spire and other stonework were needed in the 1930s.{{sfn|Fells|2014|pp=79-81}} A mobile telecommunication mast is fitted inside the spire.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Combe|first1=Victoria|title=Churches cash in on phone boom|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1376313/Churches-cash-in-on-phone-boom.html|accessdate=29 March 2015|work=Telegraph|date=30 November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Maev|title=Angel heralds heaven-sent mobile solution|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/sep/08/maevkennedy|accessdate=29 March 2015|work=Guardian|date=8 September 2000}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Bristol Blitz]] in the [[Second World War]] a bomb exploded in a nearby street, throwing a [[Rail tracks|rail]] from the tramway over the houses and into the churchyard of St Mary Redcliffe, where it became embedded in the ground. The rail is left there as a monument.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weldgen.tripod.com/bristol-history-com/id4.html |title=Memories of Bristol's Trams |accessdate=28 July 2007 |work=Bristol history.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223182951/http://weldgen.tripod.com/bristol-history-com/id4.html |archivedate=23 December 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Fells|2014|p=115}}<ref>{{cite web|title=St Mary Redcliffe|url=http://www.about-bristol.co.uk/chu-12.asp|publisher=About Bristol|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Archives==\nParish records for St Mary Redcliffe church, Bristol are held at [[Bristol Archives]] (Ref. P.St MR)  ([http://archives.bristol.gov.uk/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=P.St+MR&pos=1 online catalogue]) including baptism, marriage and burial registers. The archive also includes records of the [[incumbent (ecclesiastical)|incumbent]], churchwardens, [[overseers of the poor]], [[parochial church council]], [[chantry|chantries]], charities, estates, restoration of the church, schools, societies and [[vestry]] plus deeds, photographs, maps and plans. Records related to St Mary Redcliffe are also held at [[Berkeley Castle]] in the Muniments Room and on microfilm at Gloucestershire Archives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/results/r?_q=st%20mary%20redcliffe&_hb=oth |title=National Archives catalogue, St Mary Redcliffe |accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture and fittings==\n[[File:St Mary Redcliffe Church, Bristol, BRO Picbox-7-StMR-33, 1250x1250.jpg|thumb|left|Floorplan of St Mary Redcliffe circa 1850, the faint lines show the shapes of the [[Vault_(architecture)|vaulted arch ceilings]].]]\nSt Mary Redcliffe is one of the largest parish churches in England, and according to some sources it is the largest of all.{{sfn|Brackett|2008|p=67}}{{sfn|Ireland|1812|p=148}} The spire is also the third tallest among parish churches,<ref>{{cite web|title=St Mary Redcliffe Church|url=http://www.skyscrapernews.com/buildings.php?id=685|publisher=Skyscraper News|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref> and it is the [[tallest building in Bristol]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Redcliffe Character Appraisal|url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/sites/default/files/assets/documents/redcliffe-character-appraisal.pdf|publisher=Bristol City Council|accessdate=29 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923225148/http://www.bristol.gov.uk/sites/default/files/assets/documents/redcliffe-character-appraisal.pdf|archivedate=23 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Lady Chapel, St Mary Redcliffe.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The Lady Chapel]]\n\nSt Mary Redcliffe is cruciform in plan, with a chapel extending to the east of the chancel, and a large 13th-century tower placed asymmetrically to the north of the west front.<ref>Plan at [http://vrcoll.fa.pitt.edu/medart/image/England/Bristol/StMaryRedcliffe/Bristol-StMarysRed.html Medieval Bristol&nbsp;\u2013 St. Mary's Redcliffe]</ref> The tower was added to the building in the 13th century. It has broad angle [[buttress]]es and Y [[tracery]] to the windows. The bell stage has [[ogee]] gables and polygonal corner [[pinnacle]]s. After the collapse of the original spire in 1446 it remained truncated until the 1870s when [[George Godwin]] rebuilt it.{{sfn|Foyle|2004|pp=66-72}} The [[nave]], [[chancel]] and [[Choir (architecture)|choir]] are vaulted with richly decorated with [[Boss (architecture)|bosses]] in a variety of styles. The [[Lady Chapel]] has a star vault. The [[transept]]s has large pointed [[spandrel]]s and a [[blind arcade]] with [[mullion]]s descending from the [[clerestory]] windows. Beneath the Lady Chapel is a small crypt, with a larger one beneath the transept of three by two [[Bay (architecture)|bays]].{{sfn|Foyle|2004|pp=66-72}}\n[[File:St Mary Redcliffe Penn monument.JPG|thumb|upright|right|The monument to [[William Penn (Royal Navy officer)|William Penn]]]]\nThere is a rectangular 13th century porch on either side of the nave.{{sfn|Jenkins|1999}} The north [[Vestibule (architecture)|porch]] has an inner component dating from 1200, with black [[Purbeck Marble]] columns, and an outer hexagonal portion built in 1325 which is ogee-cusped with a [[Moorish architecture|Moorish]] appearance.{{sfn|Burrough|1970|pp=13-14}} The outer polygonal part of the north porch was built in the 14th century. It has [[crocket]]ed gables to the buttresses and is richly decorated with pinnacles and a [[quatrefoil]] [[parapet]] above a [[Lierne (vault)|lierne vault]].{{sfn|Foyle|2004|pp=66-72}}\n\nWithin the church are an oak chest with [[caryatid]]s dating from 1593. The choir stalls date from the 15th century. There are two [[baptismal font|fonts]]; one from the 13th century and the other made of marble by [[William Paty]] was made in 1755. The oak [[pulpit]] was built in the 19th century by William Bennett. A [[Wrought iron|wrought-iron]] gilded chancel screen built by [[William Edney]] in 1710 still stands under the tower.<ref name=nhle/>\n\nOn 1 June 2016 [[Purcell_(architects)|Purcell]] announced they had been awarded the contract to extend St Mary Redcliffe to include visitor amenities, step-free access and a community hub.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.purcelluk.com/news-events/news#/news/purcell-win-st-mary-redcliffe-design-competition |title=Purcell announces win of St Mary Redcliffe extension contract |accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Monuments and memorials===\n\nThe church is adorned with monuments to individuals from the history of the city, including Sir [[William Penn (Royal Navy officer)|William Penn]] (the father of [[William Penn]], founder of [[Pennsylvania]]). His [[helmet|helm]] and [[armour|half-armour]] are hung on the wall, together with the tattered banners of the Dutch ships that he captured in battle. The church also displays a rib of a whale brought back from one of his voyages by [[John Cabot]].{{sfn|Brace|1996}}\n\nThe monuments of [[William II Canynges]] (c. 1399\u20131474) and his grandfather William I Canynges both have effigies on them, as do those of Robert de Berkeley<ref name=nhle/> and of [[Philip Mede]] (c.1415-1475), a [[Member of Parliament]] and thrice [[Mayor of Bristol]]. Multiple mural monuments also exist in the church.{{sfn|Foyle|2004|pp=66-72}} Amongst the [[monumental brass]]es is one to Richard Mede (d. circa 1488), son of Philip Mede.\n\nOutside the churchyard set into the south end of a wall that runs along Redcliffe Hill is a brass drinking fountain dated 1832, with decorated with a lion's head.<ref>https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1202486</ref> This is the well head for St Mary's Conduit, and the end point of the traditional [[The St Mary Redcliffe Pipe Walk]], which is held in October every year.\n\n===Stained glass===\n[[File:St Mary Redcliffe, Bristol. Medieval Glass - geograph.org.uk - 1412314.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Some of the remaining medieval glass]]\nLittle of the early stained glass remains. In the west window of St John's Chapel, for instance, the medieval glass barely survived the destruction (said to have been caused by [[Oliver Cromwell]]'s men).<ref>{{cite web|title=Cathedral and Church Repairs|url=http://www.wessexrestoration.co.uk/news/cathedral-church-repairs-2/|publisher=Wessex Restoration|accessdate=29 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402145236/http://www.wessexrestoration.co.uk/news/cathedral-church-repairs-2/|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most of the higher portions went untouched, but others were severely damaged. In some cases the windows were impossible to repair, and clear glass was eventually introduced to replace the missing scenes. The [[Victorian era|Victorian]] stained-glass windows were created by some of the finest studios of that period.<ref name=cobb>{{cite journal |last1=Cobb|first1=Peter G.|title=The Stained Glass of St. Mary Redcliffe, Bristol|journal=Transactions of the Bristol and Gloucestershire Archaeological Society|date=1994|volume=112|pages=143\u2013166|url=http://www2.glos.ac.uk/bgas/tbgas/v112/bg112143.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[William Wailes]] produced a design for the seven-light east window following a competition launched in 1846; however, delays in raising the money caused delays in its installation. Controversy over the design meant that it was replaced with the current depiction of the Crucifixion by [[Clayton and Bell]] in 1904. The tree design in the window of the south transept was also by Wailes and was installed in 1854. In the north transept is a memorial window to Samuel Lucas who died in 1853, designed and installed by the St Helens Crown Glass Company which later became [[Pilkington]]. Another Wailes design depicting the ''Offering of the Wise Men'' was installed in the Lady Chapel, alongside one designed by Arthur O'Connor. The windows in the choir aisles are by Clayton and Bell who also designed the memorial to [[Edward Colston]] which is in the north wall of the north transept.<ref name=cobb/>\n\nThe west window was obscured by the organ until the 1860s when it was moved to make way for a depiction of the Annunciation which was designed by John Hardman Powell of [[Hardman & Co.]] and funded by Sholto Hare. Attempts to achieve some conformity with the installed work and subsequent designs lead to a further commissions for Clayton and Bell and Hardman & Co. generally as memorials to wealthy local dignitaries who had contributed to the restoration of the church.<ref name=cobb/>\n\n===Hogarth's triptych===\n[[File:Hogarth triptych.jpg|thumb|[[William Hogarth]]'s [[altarpiece]] [[triptych]] photographed at [[St Nicholas, Bristol]]]]\n[[Sealing the Tomb]], a great [[altarpiece]] [[triptych]] by [[William Hogarth]], was commissioned in 1756 to fill the east end of the chancel. The [[churchwarden]]s paid him \u00a3525 for his paintings of the three scenes depicted; the ''[[Ascension of Jesus|Ascension]]'' featuring [[Mary Magdalene]],{{sfn|Og\u00e9e|Bindman|Wagner|2001|p=262}} on a central canvas which is {{convert|22|ft}} by {{convert|19|ft}}. It is flanked by ''[[Burial of Jesus|The Sealing of the Sepulchre]]'' and the ''[[The Three Marys|Three Marys at the Tomb]]'', each of which is {{convert|13|ft|10|in}} by {{convert|12|ft}}. They are mounted in gilded frames made by [[Thomas Paty]].<ref name=fells>{{cite book|last1=Fells|first1=Maurice|title=The A\u2013Z of Curious Bristol|date=2014|publisher=History Press|isbn=978-0750956055|pages=43\u201344}}</ref> This was removed from the church by mid-Victorian liturgists, before being displayed at the [[Bristol City Museum and Art Gallery]]; it is now stored in the church of [[St Nicholas, Bristol]].{{sfn|Burrough|1970|pp=13-14}}\n\n==The church bells==\n[[File:St Mary Redcliffe ceiling 2.JPG|thumb|upright|left|The highly decorated [[vaulted ceiling]] in St Mary Redcliffe]]\nThe tower contains a total of 15 bells, one bell dating from as early as 1622 cast by Purdue and two cast by Thomas I Bilbie of the [[Bilbie family]] from [[Chew Stoke]] in 1763,<ref>{{cite web|title=Bristol, Redcliffe|url=http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?numPerPage=10&searchCountry=British+Isles&searchDiocese=Bristol&searchAmount=%3D&searchMetric=cwt&Submit=Go&sortBy=Place&sortDir=Asc&page=2&DoveID=BRISTOL+21|publisher=Dove's Guide|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref> the remainder were cast by [[John Taylor & Co]] at various dates, 1903 (9 bells), 1951 (1 bell), 1969 (1 bell) and 2012 (1 bell). The larger Bilbie (10th) bell along with the 1622 Purdue (11th) bell are included in the 50 cwt ring of 12 bells.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bells of St Mary Redcliffe|url=http://stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/our-community/guild-of-bellringers/the-bells/|publisher=St Mary Redcliffe|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe bells are hung in a cast iron and steel H-frame by John Taylor & Co dating from the major overhaul of 1903.<ref name=bbcbells/> A number of small modifications have taken place when each additional bell was added. The 50 cwt tenor bell is the largest bell in a parish church to be hung for full-circle English-Style change ringing and the 7th-largest such bell in the world, only surpassed by Liverpool Anglican Cathedral 11th (55 cwt), Wells Cathedral tenor (56 cwt), York Minster tenor (59 cwt), St Paul's Cathedral tenor, London (61 cwt), Exeter Cathedral tenor (72 cwt) and Liverpool Cathedral tenor (82 cwt).<ref>{{cite news|title=Behind the scenes of Bristol's bellringing community|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/scenes-Bristol-s-bellringing-community/story-11299609-detail/story.html|accessdate=29 March 2015|work=Bristol Post|date=10 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402172737/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/scenes-Bristol-s-bellringing-community/story-11299609-detail/story.html|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A new 8th bell was cast by John Taylor & Co in 2012 for the Queen's Diamond Jubilee, replacing the 1768 Bilbie bell, a non-swinging bell with an internal hammer fitted for use as a service bell, and chimed from within the body of the church.<ref name=bbcbells>{{cite web|title=Bristol church's 'clunking' bell to be fixed after 110 years|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-21425578|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Work Completed January&nbsp;\u2014 March 2013|url=http://www.taylorbells.co.uk/web/?q=node/65|publisher=John Taylor & Co|accessdate=29 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402103740/http://www.taylorbells.co.uk/web/?q=node%2F65|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe ring of 12 bells is augmented with two additional semitone bells. A sharp treble bell cast by John Taylor & Co in 1969 is the smallest bell in the tower and a \"flat 6th\" cast by John Taylor & Co in 1951 and allow different [[diatonic scale]]s to be rung. All the bells have been tuned on a lathe; the tenor bell was tuned in 1903 and strikes the note of B (492&nbsp;Hz).<ref name=lyndenlea/> The St Mary Redcliffe Guild of Change Ringers was founded in 1948.<ref name=bellsofstmarys>{{cite web|title=The Bells of St Mary Redcliffe|url=http://stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/files/2012/06/Bells-of-St-Mary-Redclffe.pdf|publisher=St Mary Redcliffe|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe clock chime can be heard striking the quarter chimes on the 3rd, 4th, 5th and 8th bells of the ring of 12 with the hours being struck on the largest 50 cwt (12th) tenor bell. The clock chime strikes the \"Cambridge Chimes\", commonly known as the \"[[Westminster Chimes]]\", every quarter of an hour daily from 7 am to 11 pm.<ref name=lyndenlea>{{cite web|title=St Mary the Virgin, Redcliffe, Bristol|url=http://bells.lyndenlea.info/towerinfo.php?br=bristol&twr=redcliffe|publisher=Lyndenlea|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref> The chimes are disabled outside of these hours. If the bells are in the 'up' position, the chimes are also disabled (normally during the day on Sundays). The clock was fully converted to electric operation during the 1960s. It is now driven by a Smith's of Derby synchronous motor. The old pendulum, gravity escapement and weights, etc., were removed when the clock was automated. What remains of the clock movement and electrified chiming barrel is housed in a large enclosure in the ringing room. The clock face is approximately 3&nbsp;m in diameter and is on the northern elevation.<ref name=lyndenlea/>\n\n==Choir==\nThe choir have released numerous recordings, as well as touring Europe and North America.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music / Recordings|url=http://stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/music/recordings/|publisher=St Mary Redcliffe|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Organ==\n[[File:Pipe.organ.console.arp.jpg|thumb|left|In St Mary Redcliffe, the [[Harrison & Harrison]] organ console of 1911, restored in 1990]]\n[[File:St Mary Redcliffe 9658.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The pipes of the church organ]]\nThe first [[pipe organ]] in the church, built by Harris and Byfield in 1726, was of three [[manual (music)|manuals]] and 26&nbsp;[[organ stop|stops]].<ref name=hale>{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=Paul|title=Perfection Preserved The Harrison & Harrison organ in the church of St Mary, Redcliffe, Bristol|journal=Organists Review|date=November 2010|pages=33\u201339|url=http://www.paulhale.org/pdf/PH10Nov.pdf}}</ref> It was rebuilt in 1829 and again in 1867 on either side of the chancel.<ref name=hale/> In 1912 a four-manual, 71-stop organ having over 4,300&nbsp;[[organ pipe|pipes]] was installed by [[Harrison & Harrison]].{{sfn|Aughton|2008|p=127}} Towards the end of his life Arthur Harrison said that he regarded the organ at St Mary Redcliffe as his \"finest and most characteristic work\". The organ remains essentially as he designed it in 1911.<ref name=hale/>\n\n[[Kevin Bowyer]] recorded [[Kaikhosru Shapurji Sorabji|Kaikhosru Sorabji's]] First Organ Symphony on it in 1988, for which the organ was an \"ideal choice\"; the notes to the recording describe the church as \"acoustically ideal, with a reverberation period of 3\u00bd seconds\", and notes that the organ has \"a luxuriousness of tone\" and \"a range of volume from practically inaudible to fiendishly loud\".<ref>{{cite web|title=St. Mary Redcliffe Bristol Harrison & Harrison, 1912|url=http://pleasuresofthepipes.info/Bristol-StMary-Redcliffe.html|publisher=Pleasures of the Pipes|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref> William McVicker, organist at the [[Royal Festival Hall]], has called the organ \"the finest high-[[Romantic music|Romantic]] organ ever constructed\".{{sfn|Aughton|2008|p=154}}\n\nNovember 2010 saw the first performances on the organ after an 18-month renovation by its original builders Harrison & Harrison, costing around \u00a3800,000. The organ had been disassembled and some of it taken away to the builders' workshop in [[Durham, England|Durham]].<ref>{{cite news |title='Masterpiece' church organ will play again |last1=Fells |first1=Maurice |last2=Harris |first2=Dominic |url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Masterpiece-church-organ-play/article-2844941-detail/article.html |newspaper=[[Bristol Evening Post]] |date=6 November 2010 |accessdate=7 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130421121116/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Masterpiece-church-organ-play/article-2844941-detail/article.html |archivedate=21 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The pipes were cleaned and the leather of the [[bellows]] was replaced.<ref name=hale/> The manuals were also fitted with an electronic panel for storing combinations of stop settings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why cleaning Bristol St Mary Redcliffe's organ is like working on a 4,500-piece jigsaw |url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/cleaning-Bristol-St-Mary-Redcliffe-s-organ-like-working-4-500-piece-jigsaw/article-1908379-detail/article.html |newspaper=[[Bristol Evening Post]] |date=10 March 2010 |accessdate=8 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120912113802/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/cleaning-Bristol-St-Mary-Redcliffe-s-organ-like-working-4-500-piece-jigsaw/article-1908379-detail/article.html |archivedate=12 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Organists, choirmasters and directors of music===\n\nThere is no record of the names of some of the early organists; however there is a record of several payments to Mr Nelme Rogers for playing the organ in the 1730s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carrington|first1=Douglas R.|title=The Early History of the Organs|url=http://stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/files/2012/06/The-History-of-the-Organs-Douglas-Carrington.pdf|publisher=St May Redcliffe|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref> Rogers had a long tenure from 1727 when a new organ was installed until 1772, when John Allen took over.{{sfn|Temperley|Banfield|2010|p=145}} [[Cornelius Bryan]] served as the organist from 1818 until 1840.{{sfn|Olleson|2003|p=24}} He was followed by [[Edwin Hobhouse Sircom]] until 1855 and then [[William Haydn Flood]] until 1862. For the next hundred years the post of organist was combined with that of choirmaster and was held by: [[Joseph William Lawson]] 1862\u20131906, [[Ralph Thompson Morgan]] 1906\u20131949, Kenneth Roy Long 1949\u20131952 and Ewart Garth Benson 1953\u20131968, who continued as the organist until 1987.<ref name=musicstaff/>\n\nFrom 1967 a choirmaster was appointed. The post was held by: Peter Fowler 1968, Bryan Anderson 1968\u20131980 and John Edward Marsh 1980\u20131987. From 1987 the title of the post was Director of Music and organist, with the post being held by: John Edward Marsh 1987\u20131994, Anthony John Pinel 1994\u20132003 and Andrew William Kirk since 2003.<ref name=musicstaff>{{cite web|title=Music Staff|url=http://stmaryredcliffe.co.uk/music/music-staff/|publisher=St Mary Redcliffe|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref> The assistant organists have been: John Edward Marsh 1976\u20131980, Colin Hunt 1980\u20131990, Anthony John Pinel 1990\u20131994, Graham Alsop from 1990  and Claire Alsop from 2003.<ref name=musicstaff/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Churches in Bristol]]\n* [[Grade I listed buildings in Bristol]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings and structures in Bristol]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Cite book | last=Aughton | first=Peter | title=St Mary Redcliffe: The Church and its People | publisher=Redcliffe Press | location=Bristol | year=2008 | isbn=978-1-904537-83-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Brace |first=Keith |authorlink= |title=Portrait of Bristol |year=1996 |publisher=Robert Hale |location=London |isbn=0-7091-5435-6 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Brackett|first1=Virginia|title=The Facts on File Companion to British Poetry: 17th and 18th Centuries|date=2008|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9780816063284|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Burrough|first1=T.H.B|title=Bristol (City Buildings Series)|date=1970|publisher=Studio Vista|isbn=978-0289798041